english:
  title: Preface to an Abbreviated Version of the Comprehensive Records of the Great Peace
  author: Lee Seung-so
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The way of the Confucian scholar is to illuminate the source of human nature and principle, to understand the transformations of past and present, and to cultivate these in oneself before applying them to the realm and the state. This is achieved through the Classics and History alone. To seek anything beyond these is to abandon our way and fall into heterodoxy.

    Yet the principles of the world are infinite, and the transformations of things are equally without end. Thus, beyond the Classics and History, there exist the hundred schools and various branches of learning. Each, according to their own insight, establishes doctrines and composes works. Though not all may accord perfectly with the sage's teachings, neither are they entirely without merit. They serve to broaden our knowledge and understanding, and help us recognize that the Way is vast and present everywhere. This is precisely what the scholar cannot neglect. Such is why the Comprehensive Records of the Great Peace came to be.

    Yet because it records all accounts without omission, it sprawls and rambles across five hundred scrolls. Few readers can complete it entirely. My friend, the Lord of Changning, is a man of antiquarian tastes and broad learning, a true gentleman. Having once read the Comprehensive Records and delighted in its rich prose and wondrous tales, he lamented its excessive length and lack of focus. Thus he pruned its redundancies and condensed it to fifty scrolls for easier perusal. He brought it to me and asked for a preface.

    Upon reading it, I found it like holding a beacon to murky waters—the obscure and strange became brilliantly clear; like excavating the mound of Li Mountain to reveal its hidden treasures, each revelation grew more marvelous still. It captivated the reader and dispelled all weariness. Across several thousand years, one encounters the nature and condition of spirits and ghosts in the shadowed realm, and the transformations of human character in the illuminated world. All that is wondrous, astounding, worthy of respect, and deserving of contempt stands revealed before us. One need not labor through five cartloads of books to escape the reproach of narrow vision.

    The Lord's diligence is surely worthy of praise. Yet he expressed concern: "The Master did not speak of the strange, the forceful, chaos, or spirits. Will not later scholars point to this and criticize, saying: 'This is not the writing of a sage'?"

    I replied: "The Changes record dragons and sacred diagrams; the Book of Documents preserves the patterns of the tortoise; the Poetry celebrates the dark bird and its sacred traces; the compilers of the Rituals recount the manifestations of the four divine creatures; historians record the flight of the six winged beings. The sages, in composing the Classics, preserved all these without deletion. Is there no reason for this? Indeed, as the principles of the world are infinite and the transformations of things equally boundless, we cannot reduce all to a single doctrine. The Master's silence concerns not the things themselves, but rather that people, lacking clear understanding of the Six Classics, might be led astray by the pursuit of hidden meanings and strange interpretations. Yet if one first masters the Way of the Six Classics and has attained the realm of the correct, the great, and the illumined, then even the humble talk of streets and alleys contains principle and offers instruction. How much more so when, in moments of solitude and melancholy, one reads such accounts? It becomes as though one sits with the ancients, conversing and joking together. The dull heaviness of discontent melts like ice, and the mind becomes spacious and clear. Is this not the art of tension and release? Without this, there would have been no need for the office of street historians in antiquity, nor would the art of tales survive to later generations."

    The Lord replied, "You speak truly." I thus committed this to writing and present it to him.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Comprehensive Records of the Great Peace' (太平廣記) is a famous 10th-century Chinese collection of tales and anecdotes compiled by Li Fang.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'five cartloads of books' (五車書) is a classical allusion to extensive learning.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to the 'dark bird' (玄鳥) alludes to the creation myth in the Book of Poetry and the founding of the Shang dynasty.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'six winged beings' (六鷁) refers to auspicious omens recorded in historical texts.
